{"title_page": "Non-Partisan Association", "text_new": "{{short description|Municipal political party in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Non-Partisan Association\n| native_name =\n| _subheader = Active&nbsp;municipal&nbsp;party\n| abbreviation = NPA\n| logo = Non-Partisan Association (Vancouver) logo.png\n| logo_size =\n| president = Mark Angus\n| chairman =\n| chairperson =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title =\n| leader1_name =\n| foundation = {{Start date|1937|11|13}}\n| dissolution =\n| merger =\n| split =\n| predecessor =\n| merged =\n| successor =\n| headquarters =\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Big tent]]<ref name=\"Boynton\">{{cite news |last1=Boynton |first1=Sean |title=Vancouver councillor Rebecca Bligh resigns from NPA over alleged anti-SOGI board members |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6267038/vancouver-rebecca-bligh-city-council-npa/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=Global News |date=December 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><br />[[Fiscal conservatism]]<ref>{{cite web |title=ABOUT - NPA Vancouver |url=https://npavancouver.ca/about/ |publisher=Non-Partisan Association |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |language=en-CA}}</ref>}}\n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]\n| national =\n| international =\n| student_wing =\n| youth_wing =\n| membership =\n| membership_year =\n| colours = Purple\n| colors =\n| colorcode = #7228D8\n| blank1_title = Fiscal policy\n| blank1 =\n| blank2_title = Social policy\n| blank2 =\n| seats1_title = Seats on [[Vancouver City Council|City Council]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|4|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| seats2_title = Seats on [[Vancouver Park Board|Park Board]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|2|7|hex=#7228D8}}\n| seats3_title = Seats on [[Vancouver School Board|School Board]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|3|9|hex=#7228D8}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.npavancouver.ca}}\n| country = Canada\n| state = Vancouver\n| parties_dab1 = Municipal political parties in Vancouver\n| elections_dab1 = Municipal elections in Vancouver\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Non-Partisan Association''' ('''NPA''') is a municipal political party in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada. It was established by the city's business leaders on November 13, 1937, to counteract the growing influence of the [[democratic socialist]] [[British Columbia CCF|Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Andrea |title=The CCF, NPA and Civic Change: Provincial Forces Behind Vancouver Politics 1930-1940 |url=https://ojs.library.ubc.ca/index.php/bcstudies/issue/view/173 |journal=BC Studies |date=1982 |issue=53 |page=59 |doi=10.14288/bcs.v0i53 |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MacKie\">{{cite news |last1=MacKie |first1=John |title=THIS DAY IN HISTORY: NOVEMBER 13, 1937 |url=https://vancouversun.com/News/Metro/this-day-in-history-november-13-1937/amp/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Vancouver Sun |date=November 13, 2012}}</ref> The party is generally perceived as [[centre-right]] within the Vancouver political spectrum and historically has drawn its strongest support from the business community and \"corporate downtown\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Fern|title=Vancouver Civic Political Parties: Developing a Model of Party-system Change and Stabilization|journal=BC Studies: The British Columbian Quarterly|date=1975|volume=Spring 1975|issue=25|pages=3\u201331|url=http://ojs.library.ubc.ca/index.php/bcstudies/article/view/826}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nThe NPA first fielded candidates in the December 9, 1936, municipal election, which saw their mayoral candidate, [[George Clark Miller|George Miller]], elected to office.<ref name=\"MacKie\"/> Prior to the 1939 election, a member of the NPA's executive, [[Nelson Spencer]], broke away from the party and ran independently after the NPA chose the then-incumbent Miller as its mayoral candidate instead of Spencer. The result was a right-wing vote was split, and CCF candidate [[James Lyle Telford|Lyle Telford]] was elected.<ref name=\"MacKie\"/> Telford would only serve one term before NPA candidate Jack Cornett was elected in the 1940 election, beginning a decades-long period of NPA dominance on Vancouver City Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paulsen |first1=Monte |title='New' NPA to consider name change |url=https://thetyee.ca/Blogs/TheHook/Municipal-Politics/2010/04/27/New-NPA-to-consider-name-change/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Tyee |date=April 27, 2010 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n[[File:Non-Partisan Association logo (old).png|thumb|right|The NPA's previous logo, in use until 2014.]]\n\nJennifer Clarke was chosen to be the NPA's mayoral candidate for the [[2002 Vancouver municipal election|2002 municipal election]], as opposed to the then-incumbent mayor [[Philip Owen]]. Owen had been in disagreement with the rest of the party leadership due to his support for [[harm reduction]] programs in the [[Downtown Eastside]], although Clarke stated she was also in favour of such programs. The NPA ultimately lost the mayoral race, as well as its majority on city council, which it had maintained since 1986.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mutimer |first1=David |title=Canadian Annual Review of Politics and Public Affairs 2002 |date=2008 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-0-8020-9819-1 |page=107 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=1C0JMG78fP8C&pg=PA107 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLong-time city councillor [[Sam Sullivan]] was chosen as the NPA's candidate for the [[2005 Vancouver municipal election#Mayoralty election|2005 mayoral race]],<ref>{{cite news |title=NPA mayoral race heats up |url=https://www.straight.com/article/npa-mayoral-race-heats-up |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=September 15, 2005 |language=en}}</ref> which he later won. The NPA also regained its majority on city council, winning a total of six seats.<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Summary Report: November 19, 2005 |url=http://former.vancouver.ca/ctyclerk/election2005/finalresults.htm |publisher=City of Vancouver |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Ladner]] was the NPA's mayoral candidate for the [[2008 Vancouver municipal election|2008 municipal election]] but was defeated by [[Gregor Robertson (politician)|Gregor Robertson]], the candidate for [[Vision Vancouver]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Election summary - Election 2008 - City of Vancouver Elections |url=http://former.vancouver.ca/electionresults2008/ |publisher=City of Vancouver |accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> The NPA's electoral platform during the 2008 election focused on reducing crime, improving housing affordability, leveraging the [[2010 Winter Olympics]], protecting the environment, advancing the city's arts and culture sector, and working collaboratively with senior levels of government, community groups, and the private sector.<ref>[http://www.npavancouver.ca/Portals/0/Newsfiles/NPA_Action%20Plan%20Brochure.pdf NPA Action Plan Brochure]{{dead link|date=April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe party, led by [[Suzanne Anton]] as the NPA's mayoral candidate, once again lost to Robertson and Vision Vancouver in the [[2011 Vancouver municipal election|2011 municipal election]] but elected two members to Vancouver City Council. Two members also sat on the Parks Board, and three members sat on the Vancouver School Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 election results |url=http://vancouver.ca/electionResults2011/index.htm|website=Vancouver.ca|accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2016, provincial education minister [[Mike Bernier]] fired the school trustees elected during the [[2014 Vancouver municipal election|2014 municipal election]] for failing to pass a balanced budget.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Rob |last2=Sherlock |first2=Tracy |title=B.C. education minister Bernier fires Vancouver school board |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/npa-trustees-call-on-minister-to-take-action-on-vsb/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=October 18, 2016}}</ref> NPA candidate Fraser Ballantyne was re-elected during the subsequent [[2017 Vancouver municipal by-election|2017 municipal by-election]], alongside newcomer Lisa Dominato.<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 by-election results |url=http://vancouver.ca/election/2017/results.aspx}}</ref>\n\nCity councillor Rebecca Bligh announced on December 6, 2019 that she was leaving the NPA and would continue to serve as an independent.<ref name=\"Boynton\"/> She cited concerns over the NPA's newly elected executive team, which included members of the anti-SOGI movement<ref>{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=Wanyee |title=Vancouver political party\u2019s \u2018veer to the right\u2019 not a winning strategy, say NPA party insiders |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2019/12/07/vancouver-political-partys-veer-to-the-right-not-a-winning-strategy-say-npa-party-insiders.html |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Star |date=December 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and former staff of the far-right [[Rebel News|''Rebel Media'']].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fumano |first1=Dan |title=Vancouver councillor quits NPA, citing concerns over party's shift to 'far right' |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/vancouver-councillor-quits-npa-citing-concerns-over-partys-shift-to-far-right/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=December 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Charlie |title=NPA members elect a former Rebel Media bureau chief and the B.C. Conservatives president to party board |url=https://www.straight.com/news/1330551/npa-members-elect-former-rebel-media-bureau-chief-and-bc-conservative-party-president |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=November 27, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Other high profile NPA members, such as city councillor Sarah Kirby-Yung and 2018 mayoral candidate Ken Sim, also voiced concerns over the party's perceived shift to the right.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bula |first1=Frances |title=Former Vancouver mayoral candidate Ken Sim alarmed at NPA swing to the right |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-former-vancouver-mayoral-candidate-ken-sim-alarmed-at-npa-swing-to-the/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral results ==\nThe NPA held a majority on [[Vancouver City Council]] from 1941 to 1967, 1970 to 1972, 1978 to 1982, 1986 to 2002, and from 2005 to 2008.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} It held the mayor's office from 1941 to 1958, from 1963 to 1970, from 1986 to 2002, and from 2005 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Vancouver - Mayors of Vancouver |url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/whoswho_mayors.htm |website=www.vancouverhistory.ca |publisher=The History of Metropolitan Vancouver |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> However, it has elected only three of the last eight mayors since 1972. Over the years, its opposition has been [[The Electors' Action Movement]] (TEAM) in the 1970s, the centre-left [[Coalition of Progressive Electors]] (COPE) in the 1980s and 1990s, and centre-left [[Vision Vancouver]] in the 2000s and 2010s.\n\nThere have been eleven NPA mayors of Vancouver:\n* [[Jonathan Webster Cornett|Jack (Jonathan Webster) Cornett]] (1941\u20131946)\n* [[Gerry McGeer]] (1947)\n* [[Charles E. Jones (mayor)|Charles E. Jones]] (1947\u20131948)\n* [[George Clark Miller]] (acting) (1948)\n* [[Charles Edwin Thompson]] (1949\u20131950)\n* [[Frederick Hume]] (1951\u20131958)\n* [[William Rathie]] (1963\u20131966)\n* [[Tom Campbell (mayor)|Tom Campbell]] (Independent 1967\u20131970, NPA from 1970\u20131972)\n* [[Gordon Campbell (Canadian politician)|Gordon Campbell]] (1986\u20131993)\n* [[Philip Owen]] (1993\u20132002)\n* [[Sam Sullivan]] (2005\u20132008)\n\n=== Incumbent NPA office holders ===\n* Melissa De Genova, Council\n* Sarah Kirby-Yung, Council\n* Lisa Dominato, Council\n* Rebecca Bligh, Council\n* Colleen Hardwick, Council\n* John Coupar, Park Board\n* Tricia Barker, Park Board\n* Fraser Ballantyne, School Board\n* Carmen Cho, School Board\n* Oliver Hanson, School Board\n\n=== 1996\u20132018 results ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Mayoral\n! Election year\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Position\n! Result\n|-\n! [[1996 Vancouver municipal election|1996]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Owen, Philip\" | [[Philip Owen]]\n| 50,969\n| 53.15\n| 1st\n| {{yes2|Elected}}\n|-\n! [[1999 Vancouver municipal election|1999]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Owen, Philip\" | Philip Owen\n| 51,085\n| 54.19\n| 1st\n| {{yes2|Elected}}\n|-\n! [[2002 Vancouver municipal election|2002]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Clarke, Jennifer\" | Jennifer Clarke\n| 41,936\n| 30.01\n| 2nd\n| {{no2|Not elected}}\n|-\n! [[2005 Vancouver municipal election|2005]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Sullivan, Sam\" | [[Sam Sullivan]]\n| 61,543\n| 47.34\n| 1st\n| {{yes2|Elected}}\n|-\n! [[2008 Vancouver municipal election|2008]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Ladner, Peter\" | [[Peter Ladner]]\n| 48,794\n| 39.26\n| {{decrease}} 2nd\n| {{no2|Not elected}}\n|-\n! [[2011 Vancouver municipal election|2011]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Anton, Suzanne\" | [[Suzanne Anton]]\n| 58,152\n| 40.15\n| {{steady}} 2nd\n| {{no2|Not elected}}\n|-\n! [[2014 Vancouver municipal election|2014]]\n| data-sort-value=\"LaPointe, Kirk\" | [[Kirk LaPointe]]\n| 73,443\n| 40.42\n| {{steady}} 2nd\n| {{no2|Not elected}}\n|-\n! [[2018 Vancouver municipal election|2018]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Sim, Ken\" | Ken Sim\n| 48,748\n| 28.16\n| {{steady}} 2nd\n| {{no2|Not elected}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ [[Vancouver City Council]]\n! Election year\n! Votes\n! %\n! Seats\n! +/\u2013\n|-\n! [[1996 Vancouver municipal election|1996]]\n| 422,118\n| \u2013\n| {{Composition bar|11|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n|\n|-\n! [[1999 Vancouver municipal election|1999]]\n| 361,315\n| \u2013\n| {{Composition bar|9|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{decrease}} 2\n|-\n! [[2002 Vancouver municipal election|2002]]\n| 368,068\n| \u2013\n| {{Composition bar|2|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{decrease}} 7\n|-\n! [[2005 Vancouver municipal election|2005]]\n| 498,082\n| 45.96\n| {{Composition bar|6|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{increase}} 4\n|-\n! [[2008 Vancouver municipal election|2008]]\n| 394,839\n| 38.00\n| {{Composition bar|1|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{decrease}} 5\n|-\n! [[2011 Vancouver municipal election|2011]]\n| 456,256\n| \u2013\n| {{Composition bar|2|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|-\n! [[2014 Vancouver municipal election|2014]]\n| 474,841\n| \u2013\n| {{Composition bar|3|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|-\n! [[2017 Vancouver municipal by-election|2017]]{{efn|Due to it being a by-election, voters were only asked to elect one councillor.}}\n| 13,372\n| 27.83\n| {{Composition bar|4|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|-\n! [[2018 Vancouver municipal election|2018]]\n| 347,752\n| 24.83\n| {{Composition bar|5|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of mayors of Vancouver]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Andrea Barbara Smith (1981). \"The Origins of the NPA: A Study in Vancouver Politics 1930\u20131940\". MA thesis. University of British Columbia.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.npavancouver.ca/}}\n\n{{Vancouver political parties}}\n{{Canadian Conservative Parties}}\n\n[[Category:Municipal political parties in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1937]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Canada]]\n[[Category:1937 establishments in British Columbia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Municipal political party in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Non-Partisan Association\n| native_name =\n| _subheader = Active&nbsp;municipal&nbsp;party\n| abbreviation = NPA\n| logo = Non-Partisan Association (Vancouver) logo.png\n| logo_size =\n| president = Mark Angus\n| chairman =\n| chairperson =\n| spokesperson =\n| leader1_title =\n| leader1_name =\n| foundation = {{Start date|1937|11|13}}\n| dissolution =\n| merger =\n| split =\n| predecessor =\n| merged =\n| successor =\n| headquarters =\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Big tent]]<ref name=\"Boynton\">{{cite news |last1=Boynton |first1=Sean |title=Vancouver councillor Rebecca Bligh resigns from NPA over alleged anti-SOGI board members |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6267038/vancouver-rebecca-bligh-city-council-npa/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=Global News |date=December 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><br />[[Fiscal conservatism]]<ref>{{cite web |title=ABOUT - NPA Vancouver |url=https://npavancouver.ca/about/ |publisher=Non-Partisan Association |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |language=en-CA}}</ref>}}\n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]\n| national =\n| international =\n| student_wing =\n| youth_wing =\n| membership =\n| membership_year =\n| colours = Purple\n| colors =\n| colorcode = #7228D8\n| blank1_title = Fiscal policy\n| blank1 =\n| blank2_title = Social policy\n| blank2 =\n| seats1_title = Seats on [[Vancouver City Council|City Council]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|4|11|hex=#7228D8}}\n| seats2_title = Seats on [[Vancouver Park Board|Park Board]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|2|7|hex=#7228D8}}\n| seats3_title = Seats on [[Vancouver School Board|School Board]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|3|9|hex=#7228D8}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.npavancouver.ca}}\n| country = Canada\n| state = Vancouver\n| parties_dab1 = Municipal political parties in Vancouver\n| elections_dab1 = Municipal elections in Vancouver\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Non-Partisan Association''' ('''NPA''') is a municipal political party in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada. It was established by the city's business leaders on November 13, 1937, to counteract the growing influence of the [[democratic socialist]] [[British Columbia CCF|Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Andrea |title=The CCF, NPA and Civic Change: Provincial Forces Behind Vancouver Politics 1930-1940 |url=https://ojs.library.ubc.ca/index.php/bcstudies/issue/view/173 |journal=BC Studies |date=1982 |issue=53 |page=59 |doi=10.14288/bcs.v0i53 |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MacKie\">{{cite news |last1=MacKie |first1=John |title=THIS DAY IN HISTORY: NOVEMBER 13, 1937 |url=https://vancouversun.com/News/Metro/this-day-in-history-november-13-1937/amp/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Vancouver Sun |date=November 13, 2012}}</ref> The party is generally perceived as [[centre-right]] within the Vancouver political spectrum and historically has drawn its strongest support from the business community and \"corporate downtown\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Fern|title=Vancouver Civic Political Parties: Developing a Model of Party-system Change and Stabilization|journal=BC Studies: The British Columbian Quarterly|date=1975|volume=Spring 1975|issue=25|pages=3\u201331|url=http://ojs.library.ubc.ca/index.php/bcstudies/article/view/826}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nThe NPA first fielded candidates in the December 9, 1936, municipal election, which saw their mayoral candidate, [[George Clark Miller|George Miller]], elected to office.<ref name=\"MacKie\"/> Prior to the 1939 election, a member of the NPA's executive, [[Nelson Spencer]], broke away from the party and ran independently after the NPA chose the then-incumbent Miller as its mayoral candidate instead of Spencer. The result was a right-wing vote was split, and CCF candidate [[James Lyle Telford|Lyle Telford]] was elected.<ref name=\"MacKie\"/> Telford would only serve one term before NPA candidate Jack Cornett was elected in the 1940 election, beginning a decades-long period of NPA dominance on Vancouver City Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paulsen |first1=Monte |title='New' NPA to consider name change |url=https://thetyee.ca/Blogs/TheHook/Municipal-Politics/2010/04/27/New-NPA-to-consider-name-change/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Tyee |date=April 27, 2010 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n[[File:Non-Partisan Association logo (old).png|thumb|right|The NPA's previous logo, in use until 2014.]]\n\nJennifer Clarke was chosen to be the NPA's mayoral candidate for the [[2002 Vancouver municipal election|2002 municipal election]], as opposed to the then-incumbent mayor [[Philip Owen]]. Owen had been in disagreement with the rest of the party leadership due to his support for [[harm reduction]] programs in the [[Downtown Eastside]], although Clarke stated she was also in favour of such programs. The NPA ultimately lost the mayoral race, as well as its majority on city council, which it had maintained since 1986.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mutimer |first1=David |title=Canadian Annual Review of Politics and Public Affairs 2002 |date=2008 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-0-8020-9819-1 |page=107 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=1C0JMG78fP8C&pg=PA107 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLong-time city councillor [[Sam Sullivan]] was chosen as the NPA's candidate for the [[2005 Vancouver municipal election#Mayoralty election|2005 mayoral race]],<ref>{{cite news |title=NPA mayoral race heats up |url=https://www.straight.com/article/npa-mayoral-race-heats-up |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=September 15, 2005 |language=en}}</ref> which he later won. The NPA also regained its majority on city council, winning a total of six seats.<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Summary Report: November 19, 2005 |url=http://former.vancouver.ca/ctyclerk/election2005/finalresults.htm |publisher=City of Vancouver |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Ladner]] was the NPA's mayoral candidate for the [[2008 Vancouver municipal election|2008 municipal election]] but was defeated by [[Gregor Robertson (politician)|Gregor Robertson]], the candidate for [[Vision Vancouver]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Election summary - Election 2008 - City of Vancouver Elections |url=http://former.vancouver.ca/electionresults2008/ |publisher=City of Vancouver |accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> The NPA's electoral platform during the 2008 election focused on reducing crime, improving housing affordability, leveraging the [[2010 Winter Olympics]], protecting the environment, advancing the city's arts and culture sector, and working collaboratively with senior levels of government, community groups, and the private sector.<ref>[http://www.npavancouver.ca/Portals/0/Newsfiles/NPA_Action%20Plan%20Brochure.pdf NPA Action Plan Brochure]{{dead link|date=April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe party, led by [[Suzanne Anton]] as the NPA's mayoral candidate, once again lost to Robertson and Vision Vancouver in the [[2011 Vancouver municipal election|2011 municipal election]] but elected two members to Vancouver City Council. Two members also sat on the Parks Board, and three members sat on the Vancouver School Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 election results |url=http://vancouver.ca/electionResults2011/index.htm|website=Vancouver.ca|accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2016, provincial education minister [[Mike Bernier]] fired the school trustees elected during the [[2014 Vancouver municipal election|2014 municipal election]] for failing to pass a balanced budget.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Rob |last2=Sherlock |first2=Tracy |title=B.C. education minister Bernier fires Vancouver school board |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/npa-trustees-call-on-minister-to-take-action-on-vsb/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=October 18, 2016}}</ref> NPA candidate Fraser Ballantyne was re-elected during the subsequent [[2017 Vancouver municipal by-election|2017 municipal by-election]], alongside newcomer Lisa Dominato.<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 by-election results |url=http://vancouver.ca/election/2017/results.aspx}}</ref>\n\nCity councillor Rebecca Bligh announced on December 6, 2019, that she was leaving the NPA and would continue to serve as an independent.<ref name=\"Boynton\"/> She cited concerns over the NPA's newly elected executive team, which included members of the anti-SOGI movement<ref>{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=Wanyee |title=Vancouver political party\u2019s \u2018veer to the right\u2019 not a winning strategy, say NPA party insiders |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2019/12/07/vancouver-political-partys-veer-to-the-right-not-a-winning-strategy-say-npa-party-insiders.html |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Star |date=December 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and former staff of the far-right [[Rebel News|''Rebel Media'']].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fumano |first1=Dan |title=Vancouver councillor quits NPA, citing concerns over party's shift to 'far right' |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/vancouver-councillor-quits-npa-citing-concerns-over-partys-shift-to-far-right/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=Vancouver Sun |date=December 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Charlie |title=NPA members elect a former Rebel Media bureau chief and the B.C. Conservatives president to party board |url=https://www.straight.com/news/1330551/npa-members-elect-former-rebel-media-bureau-chief-and-bc-conservative-party-president |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=November 27, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Other high profile NPA members, such as city councillor Sarah Kirby-Yung and 2018 mayoral candidate Ken Sim, also voiced concerns over the party's perceived shift to the right.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bula |first1=Frances |title=Former Vancouver mayoral candidate Ken Sim alarmed at NPA swing to the right |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-former-vancouver-mayoral-candidate-ken-sim-alarmed-at-npa-swing-to-the/ |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral results ==\nThe NPA held a majority on [[Vancouver City Council]] from 1941 to 1967, 1970 to 1972, 1978 to 1982, 1986 to 2002, and from 2005 to 2008.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} It held the mayor's office from 1941 to 1958, from 1963 to 1970, from 1986 to 2002, and from 2005 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Vancouver - Mayors of Vancouver |url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/whoswho_mayors.htm |website=www.vancouverhistory.ca |publisher=The History of Metropolitan Vancouver |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> However, it has elected only three of the last eight mayors since 1972. Over the years, its opposition has been [[The Electors' Action Movement]] (TEAM) in the 1970s, the centre-left [[Coalition of Progressive Electors]] (COPE) in the 1980s and 1990s, and centre-left [[Vision Vancouver]] in the 2000s and 2010s.\n\nThere have been eleven NPA mayors of Vancouver:\n* [[Jonathan Webster Cornett|Jack (Jonathan Webster) Cornett]] (1941\u20131946)\n* [[Gerry McGeer]] (1947)\n* [[Charles E. Jones (mayor)|Charles E. Jones]] (1947\u20131948)\n* [[George Clark Miller]] (acting) (1948)\n* [[Charles Edwin Thompson]] (1949\u20131950)\n* [[Frederick Hume]] (1951\u20131958)\n* [[William Rathie]] (1963\u20131966)\n* [[Tom Campbell (mayor)|Tom Campbell]] (Independent 1967\u20131970, NPA from 1970\u20131972)\n* [[Gordon Campbell (Canadian politician)|Gordon Campbell]] (1986\u20131993)\n* [[Philip Owen]] (1993\u20132002)\n* [[Sam Sullivan]] (2005\u20132008)\n\n=== Incumbent NPA office holders ===\n* Melissa De Genova, Council\n* Sarah Kirby-Yung, Council\n* Lisa Dominato, Council\n* Rebecca Bligh, Council\n* Colleen Hardwick, Council\n* John Coupar, Park Board\n* Tricia Barker, Park Board\n* Fraser Ballantyne, School Board\n* Carmen Cho, School Board\n* Oliver Hanson, School Board\n\n=== 1996\u20132018 results ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Mayoral\n! Election year\n! Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Position\n! Result\n|-\n! [[1996 Van